ft: 3px solid grey; background:#e3d9ff;\" | {{Center|\u2014}}\n| 6 September 1943\n| 12:10\n| style=\"background:#C0EFBA\" | B-17*{{sfn|Prien|Stemmer|Rodeike|Bock|2010|p=556}}\n| south of [[Reims]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=152}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"10\" | \u2013 7. ''Staffel'' of ''Jagdgeschwader'' 26 \"Schlageter\" \u2013{{sfn|Matthews|Foreman|2015|p=998}}<br /><small>On the Western Front \u2014 1 October \u2013 31 December 1943</small>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#e3d9ff;\" | {{Center|\u2014}}\n| 10 October 1943\n| 15:35\n| style=\"background:#C0EFBA\" | B-17*{{sfn|Prien|Stemmer|Rodeike|Bock|2010|p=556}}\n| northeast of [[M\u00fcnster]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=165}}\n| style=\"border-left: 3px solid grey;\" | 7\n| 30 December 1943\n| 14:00\n| P-47\n| {{Convert|12|km|mi|abbr=on}} southeast of [[Beauvais]]{{sfn|Prien|Stemmer|Rodeike|Bock|2010|p=557}}{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=192}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:#e3d9ff;\" | {{Center|\u2014}}\n| 14 October 1943\n| 13:35\n| style=\"background:#C0EFBA\" | B-17*\n| north of [[Koblenz]]{{sfn|Prien|Stemmer|Rodeike|Bock|2010|p=556}}{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=167}}\n| style=\"border-left: 3px solid grey;\" | 8\n| 30 December 1943\n| 14:36\n| style=\"background:#C0EFBA\" | B-17*\n| {{Convert|32|km|mi|abbr=on}} west-northwest of [[Arras]]{{sfn|Prien|Stemmer|Rodeike|Bock|2010|p=557}}{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=192}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"10\" | \u2013 7. ''Staffel'' of ''Jagdgeschwader'' 26 \"Schlageter\" \u2013{{sfn|Matthews|Foreman|2015|pp=998\u2013999}}<br /><small>On the Western Front and in Defense of the Reich \u2014 1 January \u2013 31 December 1944</small>\n|-\n| 9\n| 5 January 1944\n| 13:14\n| B-17\n| vicinity of [[Miraumont]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=196}}\n| style=\"border-left: 3px solid grey;\" | 14\n| 25 February 1944\n| 14:45\n| style=\"background:#C0EFBA\" | [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator|B-24]]*\n| [[Nothweiler]]-west of [[Bad Bergzabern]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=222}}\n|-\n| 10\n| 11 January 1944\n| 13:15\n| P-47\n| Backum, near [[Lingen, Germany|Lingen]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=199}}\n| style=\"border-left: 3px solid grey;\" | 15\n| 25 February 1944\n| style=\"background:#faecc8\" | 15:20?{{Refn|According to Matthews and Foreman claimed at 15:22.{{sfn|Matthews|Foreman|2015|p=999}}|group=\"Note\"}}\n| style=\"background:pink;\" | B-17&\n| [[Wilgartswiesen]]-[[Pirmasens]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=222}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:#e3d9ff;\" | {{Center|\u2014}}\n| 29 January 1944\n| style=\"background:#faecc8\" | 11:25?{{Refn|According to Matthews and Foreman claimed at 12:00.{{sfn|Matthews|Foreman|2015|p=998}}|group=\"Note\"}}\n| style=\"background:#C0EFBA\" | B-24*\n| north of [[Trier]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=205}}\n| style=\"border-left: 3px solid grey;\" | 16\n| 12 April 1944\n| 13:10\n| style=\"background:#C0EFBA\" | B-24*\n| {{Convert|18|km|mi|abbr=on}} north of [[Namur]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=240}}\n|-\n| 11\n| 4 February 1944\n| 12:00\n| B-24\n| {{Convert|10|km|mi|abbr=on}} southeast of [[Albert, Somme|Albert]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=208}}\n| style=\"border-left: 3px solid grey;\" | 17\n| 24 April 1944\n| 12:22\n| style=\"background:#C0EFBA\" | B-17*\n| northeast of [[Saint-Dizier]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=248}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:#e3d9ff;\" | {{Center|\u2014}}\n| 8 February 1944\n| 11:10\n| P-47\n| north of [[Laon]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=210}}\n| style=\"border-left: 3px solid grey;\" | 18\n| 27 April 1944\n| 17:42\n| P-47\n| southwest of Reims{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=250}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:#e3d9ff;\" | {{Center|\u2014}}\n| 8 February 1944\n| 11:12\n| P-47\n| north of Laon{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=210}}\n| style=\"border-left: 3px solid grey;\" | 19\n| 29 April 1944\n| 13:35\n| style=\"background:#C0EFBA\" | B-17*\n| {{Convert|5|km|mi|abbr=on}} southeast of [[Roubaix]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=250}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:#e3d9ff;\" | {{Center|\u2014}}\n| 11 February 1944\n| 13:50\n| [[Lockheed P-38 Lightning|P-38]]\n| southeast of [[Valenciennes]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=212}}\n| style=\"border-left: 3px solid grey;\" | 20\n| 8 May 1944\n| 10:32\n| P-47\n| {{Convert|6|km|mi|abbr=on}} north of [[Soissons]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=254}}\n|-\n| 12\n| 18 February 1944\n| style=\"background:#faecc8\" | 12:05?{{Refn|According to Matthews and Foreman claimed at 12:10.{{sfn|Matthews|Foreman|2015|p=998}}|group=\"Note\"}}\n| [[Hawker Typhoon|Typhoon]]\n| north of Amiens{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=214}}\n| style=\"border-left: 3px solid grey;\" | 21\n| 11 May 1944\n| 14:00\n| B-24\n| {{Convert|44|km|mi|abbr=on}} west of [[Chartres]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=256}}<br />Bazoches\n|-\n| style=\"background:#e3d9ff;\" | {{Center|\u2014}}\n| 24 February 1944\n| 12:25\n| style=\"background:#C0EFBA\" | B-17*\n| northwest of [[Ascheberg (Westfalen)|Ascheberg]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=220}}\n| style=\"border-left: 3px solid grey; background:#e3d9ff;\" | {{Center|\u2014}}\n| 15 June 1944\n| {{Center|\u2014}}\n| [[North American P-51 Mustang|P-51]]\n| east of [[Bonneval, Eure-et-Loir|Bonneval]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=280}}\n|-\n| 13\n| 24 February 1944\n| 14:00\n| B-24\n| [[A\u00dflar]], {{Convert|5|km|mi|abbr=on}} northwest of [[Wetzlar]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=220}}\n| style=\"border-left: 3px solid grey;\" | 22\n| 23 December 1944\n| 12:57\n| [[Avro Lancaster|Lancaster]]\n| west of [[Cologne]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=391}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:#e3d9ff;\" | {{Center|\u2014}}\n| 24 February 1944\n| 14:20\n| P-51\n| northwest of Wetzlar-southeast of [[Bonn]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=220}}\n| style=\"border-left: 3px solid grey;\" | 23\n| 23 December 1944\n| 13:01\n| Lancaster\n| northwest of Cologne-north-northwest of [[D\u00fcren]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=391}}\n|}\n\n===Awards===\n* [[German Cross]] in Gold on 16 April 1944 as ''[[Leutnant]]'' in the 7./''Jagdgeschwader'' 26{{sfn|Patzwall|Scherzer|2001|p=364}}\n* [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross]] on 12 March 1945 as ''[[Oberleutnant]]'' and ''Gruppenkommandeur'' of the II./''Jagdgeschwader'' 26 \"Schlageter\"{{sf|Scherzer|2007|p=610}}{{sfn|Fellgiebel|2000|p=283}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=\"Note\"}}\n\n==References==\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |last1=Bergstr\u00f6m\n  |first1=Christer\n  |last2=Antipov\n  |first2=Vlad\n  |last3=Sundin\n  |first3=Claes\n  |year=2003\n  |title=Graf & Grislawski \u2013 A Pair of Aces\n  |location=Hamilton MT\n  |publisher=Eagle Editions\n  |isbn=978-0-9721060-4-7\n  |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |last=Caldwell\n  |first=Donald L.\n  |year=1991\n  |title=JG 26: Top Guns of the Luftwaffe\n  |location=New York\n  |publisher=Ivy Books\n  |isbn=978-0-8041-1050-1\n  |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |last=Caldwell\n  |first=Donald L.\n  |year=1998\n  |title=JG 26 War Diary: Volume Two 1943\u20131945\n  |location=London\n  |publisher=Grub Street\n  |isbn=978-1-898697-86-2\n  |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |last=Fellgiebel\n  |first=Walther-Peer\n  |authorlink=Walther-Peer Fellgiebel\n  |year=2000\n  |origyear=1986\n  |title=Die Tr\u00e4ger des Ritterkreuzes des Eisernen Kreuzes 1939\u20131945 \u2014 Die Inhaber der h\u00f6chsten Auszeichnung des Zweiten Weltkrieges aller Wehrmachtteile\n  |trans-title=The Bearers of the Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross 1939\u20131945 \u2014 The Owners of the Highest Award of the Second World War of all Wehrmacht Branches\n  |language=German\n  |location=Friedberg, Germany\n  |publisher=Podzun-Pallas\n  |isbn=978-3-7909-0284-6\n  |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |last=Girbig\n  |first=Werner\n  |year=1997\n  |title=Start im Morgengrauen\n  |trans-title=Takeoff at Dawn\n  |language=German\n  |location=Stuttgart, Germany\n  |publisher=Motorbuch Verlag\n  |isbn=978-3-613-01292-9\n  |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |last1=Matthews\n  |first1=Andrew Johannes\n  |last2=Foreman\n  |first2=John\n  |year=2015\n  |title=Luftwaffe Aces \u2014 Biographies and Victory Claims \u2014 Volume 3 M\u2013R\n  |location=Walton-on-Thames, UK\n  |publisher=Red Kite\n  |isbn=978-1-906592-20-2\n  |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{Cite web\n  |last=Meyer\n  |first=Harald\n  |date=August 2010\n  |website=www.stadt-bobingen.de\n  |title=Unfallsituation der Bundeswehr w\u00e4hrend des Aufbaus\n  |trans-title=Accidents Situation of the Bundeswehr during its Creation\n  |url=https://www.stadt-bobingen.de/Naehere-Informationen-zu-Ludger-Hoelker.o4323.html\n  |language=German\n  |location=F\u00fcrstenfeldbruck, Germany\n  |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |last1=Manrho\n  |first1=John\n  |last2=P\u00fctz\n  |first2=Ron\n  |year=2004\n  |title=Bodenplatte: The Luftwaffe's Last Hope-The Attack on Allied Airfields, New Year's Day 1945\n  |location=Crowborough, UK\n  |publisher=Hikoki Publications\n  |isbn=978-1-902109-40-4\n  |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |last=Obermaier\n  |first=Ernst \n  |year=1989\n  |title=Die Ritterkreuztr\u00e4ger der Luftwaffe Jagdflieger 1939 \u2013 1945\n  |trans-title=The Knight's Cross Bearers of the Luftwaffe Fighter Force 1939 \u2013 1945\n  |language=German\n  |location=Mainz, Germany\n  |publisher=Verlag Dieter Hoffmann\n  |isbn=978-3-87341-065-7\n  |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |last1=Patzwall\n  |first1=Klaus D. \n  |last2=Scherzer\n  |first2=Veit \n  |year=2001\n  |title=Das Deutsche Kreuz 1941 \u2013 1945 Geschichte und Inhaber Band II\n  |trans-title=The German Cross 1941 \u2013 1945 History and Recipients Volume 2\n  |language=German\n  |location=Norderstedt, Germany\n  |publisher=Verlag Klaus D. Patzwall\n  |isbn=978-3-931533-45-8\n  |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |last1=Prien\n  |first1=Jochen\n  |last2=Stemmer\n  |first2=Gerhard\n  |last3=Rodeike\n  |first3=Peter\n  |last4=Bock\n  |first4=Winfried\n  |year=2010\n  |title=Die Jagdfliegerverb\u00e4nde der Deutschen Luftwaffe 1934 bis 1945\u2014Teil 10/IV\u2014Einsatz im Westen\u20141.1. bis 31.12.1943\n  |trans-title=The Fighter Units of the German Air Force 1934 to 1945\u2014Part 10/IV\u2014Action in the West\u20141 January to 31 December 1943\n  |language=German\n  |location=Eutin, Germany\n  |publisher=Struve-Druck\n  |isbn=978-3-923457-92-2\n  |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |last=Scherzer\n  |first=Veit \n  |year=2007\n  |title=Die Ritterkreuztr\u00e4ger 1939\u20131945 Die Inhaber des Ritterkreuzes des Eisernen Kreuzes 1939 von Heer, Luftwaffe, Kriegsmarine, Waffen-SS, Volkssturm sowie mit Deutschland verb\u00fcndeter Streitkr\u00e4fte nach den Unterlagen des Bundesarchives\n  |trans-title=The Knight's Cross Bearers 1939\u20131945 The Holders of the Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross 1939 by Army, Air Force, Navy, Waffen-SS, Volkssturm and Allied Forces with Germany According to the Documents of the Federal Archives\n  |language=German\n  |location=Jena, Germany\n  |publisher=Scherzers Miltaer-Verlag\n  |isbn=978-3-938845-17-2\n  |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n  |last=Weal\n  |first=John\n  |year=2011\n  |title=Fw 190 Defence of the Reich Aces\n  |location=Oxford, UK\n  |publisher=[[Osprey Publishing]]\n  |isbn=978-1-84603-482-4\n  |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{Cite web\n  |website=[[Bundeswehr]]\n  |title=Im Ehrenmal der Bundeswehr namentlich genannte verstorbene Bundeswehrangeh\u00f6rige\n  |trans-title=Deceased Bundeswehr Members Named in the Bundeswehr Memorial\n  |language=German\n  |url=https://www.bundeswehr.de/resource/blob/142874/20b0959421dfdff814bbb4c7ee9d017d/uebersicht-verstorbene-data.pdf\n  |ref={{sfnRef|Ehrenmal der Bundeswehr}}\n  |accessdate=6 April 2020\n}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{succession box|\nbefore=''Major'' [[Anton Hackl]]|\nafter=''Hauptmann'' Paul Schauder|\ntitle=''Gruppenkommandeur'' of [[Jagdgeschwader 26|II./JG 26]] |\nyears=30 January 1945 \u2013 22 February 1945\n}}\n{{succession box|\nbefore=''Major'' Alfred Lindenberger|\nafter=''Hauptmann'' Karl-Heinz Dietsche|\ntitle=''Gruppenkommandeur'' of [[Jagdgeschwader 300|II./JG 300]] |\nyears=23 February 1945 \u2013 16 April 1945\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Subject bar\n| portal1=Aviation\n| portal2=Biography\n| portal3=Military of Germany\n| portal4=World War II\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Radener, Waldemar}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:1957 deaths]]\n[[Category:Luftwaffe pilots]]\n[[Category:German World War II flying aces]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Gold German Cross]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross]]\n[[Category:Pilots who performed an aerial ramming]]\n[[Category:German Air Force pilots]]\n[[Category:Aviators killed in aviation accidents or incidents]]\n[[Category:People from H\u00f6xter]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Westphalia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German fighter ace and Knight's Cross recipient}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name=Waldemar Radener\n|birth_date=24 January 1921\n|death_date={{death date and age|1957|1|8|1921|1|24|df=y}}\n|image=\n|caption=\n|birth_place=[[H\u00f6xter|L\u00fcchtringen]]\n|death_place=[[Schongau, Bavaria|Schongau]]\n|nickname=\n|allegiance={{flag|Nazi Germany}} (to 1945)<br />{{flag|West Germany}}\n|branch={{Luftwaffe}} (''[[Wehrmacht]]'')<br />{{GAF}} (''[[Bundeswehr]]'')\n|serviceyears=1939\u20131945<br>1956\u20131957\n|rank=''[[Oberleutnant]]'' (Wehrmacht)<br />''[[Hauptmann]]'' (Bundeswehr) \n|unit=[[JG 26]]<br />[[JG 300]]\n|commands=II./JG 26<br />II./JG 300\n|battles={{hidden\n|''See battles''\n|[[World War II]]\n*[[Western Front (World War II)|Western Front]]\n:*[[Defense of the Reich]]\n:*[[Operation Overlord]]\n:*[[Operation Bodenplatte]]\n|-\n|headerstyle=background:#dbdbdb\n|style=text-align:center;\n}}\n|awards=[[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross]]\n|laterwork=}}\n\n'''Waldemar Radener'''{{refn|According to Scherzer later named Waldemar Radener-Blaschke.{{sf|Scherzer|2007|p=610}}|group=\"Note\"}} (24 January 1921 \u2013 8 January 1957) was a German [[Luftwaffe]] [[military aviation|military aviator]] and [[fighter ace]] during [[World War II]]. He is credited with 37 aerial victories, all of which claimed over the [[Western Front (World War II)|Western Front]] and in [[Defense of the Reich]].\n\nBorn in [[H\u00f6xter|L\u00fcchtringen]], Radener grew up in the [[Weimar Republic]] and [[Nazi Germany]]. He joined the military service in the Luftwaffe and was trained as a fighter pilot. Following flight training,{{refn|Flight training in the Luftwaffe progressed through the levels A1, A2 and B1, B2, referred to as A/B flight training. A training included theoretical and practical training in aerobatics, navigation, long-distance flights and dead-stick landings. The B courses included high-altitude flights, instrument flights, night landings and training to handle the aircraft in difficult situations.{{sfn|Bergstr\u00f6m|Antipov|Sundin|2003|p=17}}|group=\"Note\"}} he was posted to [[Jagdgeschwader 26|''Jagdgeschwader'' 26]] \"Schlageter\" (JG&nbsp;26\u201426th Fighter Wing) in February 1943. Flying with this wing, Radener claimed his first aerial victory on 13 March 1943 on the Western Front over a [[Royal Air Force]] fighter aircraft which was not confirmed. After he had temporarily led 6. ''[[Organization of the Luftwaffe (1933\u20131945)#Staffel|Staffel]]'' (6th squadron) of JG&nbsp;26 in late 1943, he was officially appointed squadron leader of 7. ''Staffel'' (7th squadron) of JG&nbsp;26 in February 1944. In late January 1945, Radener was given command of II. ''Gruppe'' (2nd group) of JG&nbsp;26. In late February 1945, he transferred to [[Jagdgeschwader 300|''Jagdgeschwader'' 300]] (JG&nbsp;300\u2014300th Fighter Wing) where he commanded II. ''Gruppe'' of JG&nbsp;300. On 12 March, he was awarded the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross]] for his service with JG&nbsp;26. After World War II, he joined the [[German Air Force]] and was killed in a flying accident 8 January 1957.\n\n==Early life==\nRadener was born on 24 January 1921 at L\u00fcchtrigen, present-day part of [[H\u00f6xter]], at the time in the [[Province of Westphalia]], a [[Free State of Prussia]] in the [[Weimar Republic]].{{sfn|Obermaier|1989|p=183}}\n\n==World War II==\nWorld War II in Europe began on Friday 1 September 1939 when German forces invaded Poland. Following flight training, ''[[Leutnant]]'' Radener joined 4. ''Staffel'' of [[Jagdgeschwader 26|''Jagdgeschwader'' 26]] \"Schlageter\" (JG&nbsp;26\u201426th Fighter Wing) on 28 February 1943.{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=33}} Equipped with the [[Focke Wulf Fw 190]]&nbsp;A-4, his squadron was part of II. ''[[Organization of the Luftwaffe (1933\u201345)#Gruppe|Gruppe]]'' (2nd group) of JG&nbsp;26 and at the time under the of command of ''Major'' [[Wilhelm-Ferdinand Galland]] and based at [[Vitry-En-Artois Airport|Vitry-En-Artois Airfield]] in northern France.{{sfn|Prien|Stemmer|Rodeike|Bock|2010|pp=550\u2013551}} Radener filed his first aerial victory claim on 13 March which was not confirmed. The [[Supermarine Spitfire]] fighter came from either the [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] (RCAF) [[402 Squadron|No. 402]] or [[403 Helicopter Operational Training Squadron|No. 403 Squadron]] and claimed shot down east of [[\u00c9taples]].{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=36}} His first confirmed aerial victory came on 3 May. That day, he shot down a [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF) Spitfire {{Convert|20|km|mi|abbr=off}} west of the [[Baie de Somme]].{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=53}}\n\n[[File:Combatbox.gif|thumb|right|upright=1|Combat box of a 12-plane B-17 squadron. Three such boxes completed a 36-plane group box.<br/>1. Lead Element<br/>2. High Element<br/>3. Low Element<br/>4. Low Low Element]]\nOn 14 May, Radener claimed a ''Herausschuss'' (separation shot) over a [[United States Army Air Forces]] (USAAF) [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress]] bomber from the [[351st Missile Wing|351st Bombardment Group]] northwest of [[Antwerp]]. A ''Herausschuss'' was a severely damaged heavy bomber forced to separate from his [[combat box]] which normally was counted as an aerial victory. In this instance, Radener was not credited with an aerial victory.{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=58}} The USAAF [[Eighth Air Force|VIII Bomber Command]] flew its fist daylight mission during the [[Battle of the Ruhr]] on 22 June. In defense of this attack, Radener claimed a [[Republic P-47 Thunderbolt]] escort fighter shot down {{Convert|10|-|15|km|mi|abbr=on}} northwest of [[Domburg]].{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|pp=104, 106}} Four days later, the VIII&nbsp;Bomber Command attacked the [[V\u00e9lizy \u2013 Villacoublay Air Base|Villacoublay Airfield]]. Defending against this attack, Radener shot down a P-47 from the [[56th Fighter Group]] {{Convert|10|km|mi|abbr=on}} north-northwest of [[Le Tr\u00e9port]].{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|pp=110\u2013111}} VIII&nbsp;Bomber Command dispatched 237 B-17 on 4 July, attacking various targets in France, including the aircraft factories at [[Nantes]] and [[Le Mans]], as well as the [[U-boat pen]] at [[La Pallice]]. This attack force was escorted by RAF Spitfire fighters of which Radener claimed one shot down. This claim however was not confirmed.{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=114}} On 30 July he claimed two USAAF P-47 fighters from the [[78th Fighter Group]] and 56th&nbsp;Fighter Group near [[Arnhem]] and south of [[Werkendam]].{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=130}}\n\n===Squadron leader and group commander===\nOn 17 August 1943, during the [[Schweinfurt-Regensburg mission]], the ''[[Gruppenkommandeur]]'' (group commander) Galland, was [[killed in action]].{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=139}} In consequence, ''Hauptmann'' [[Johannes Naumann]] was temporarily given command of II. ''Gruppe''. Naumann had led 6. ''Staffel'' until then and Radener was chosen as his successor as ''[[Staffelkapit\u00e4n]]'' (squadron leader) of the ''Staffel''. On 9 September, ''Oberstleutnant'' [[Johannes Seifert]] was officially appointed ''Gruppenkommandeur'' of II. ''Gruppe'' and Naumann returned to lead his 6. ''Staffel''.{{sfn|Prien|Stemmer|Rodeike|Bock|2010|p=550}} Following the integration on 10. ''Staffel'' into JG&nbsp;26 on 1 October, 6. ''Staffel'' was re-designated to 7. ''Staffel''.{{sfn|Prien|Stemmer|Rodeike|Bock|2010|p=547}} The USAAF [[Eighth Air Force|VIII Bomber Command]] targeted [[Ludwigshafen]] on 30 December. That day, Radener claimed his fifth heavy bomber destroyed.{{sfn|Weal|2011|pp=51\u201352}}\n\n[[File:Ellgaard, Ich ramme 1944.jpg|thumb|upright|left|A 1944 drawing by [[Helmuth Ellgaard]] illustrating \"ramming\"]]\nRadener shot down a P-47 fighter from the [[353rd Fighter Group]] on 11 January 1944. This was his 10th aerial victory claim and the combat took place at Backum, near [[Lingen, Germany|Lingen]].{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=199}} On 9 Febraury, Radener officially became the ''Staffelkapit\u00e4n'' of 7. ''Staffel'' when Naumann was transferred again.{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=211}} He was awarded the [[German Cross]] in Gold ({{lang|de|Deutsches Kreuz in Gold}}) on 16 April for 16 aerial victories.{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=244}} On 11 May, Radener downed a [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator]] bomber from the [[487th Air Expeditionary Wing|487th Bombardment Group]] but then accidentally [[Aerial ramming|rammed]] a second B-24 in his [[Focke-Wulf Fw 190]]&nbsp;A-8 (''Werknummer'' 680120\u2014factory number). He [[parachute|bailed out]] with minor injuries while the B-24 returned to England.{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|pp=256, 259}} On 15 June, Radener claimed an unconfirmed aerial victory over a USAAF [[North American P-51 Mustang]] fighter from the [[339th Fighter Group]] in combat east of [[Bonneval, Eure-et-Loir|Bonneval]].{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=280}} Shortly after, he was also shot down by another P-51 from the 339th&nbsp;Fighter&nbsp;Group. He bailed out but his parachute failed to fully deploy after it got entangled with his Fw&nbsp;190&nbsp;A-8 (''Werknummer'' 730934) and suffered injuries on landing keeping him hospitalised until the end of the month. During his convalescance, he was temporarily replaced by ''Leutnant'' [[Heinz-Gerhard Vogt]] as leader of 7. ''Staffel''.{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|pp=278, 280}}\n\nOn 11 September, Radener returned from his injury leave and retained his command of 7. ''Staffel'' of JG&nbsp;26.{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=346}} He claimed his last two aerial victories on 23 December, taking his total to 23 aerial victories. That day, the RAF [[RAF Bomber Command|Bomber Command]] attacked German transportation infrastructure east of combat area of the [[Battle of the Bulge]] which was fought in the [[Ardennes]]. In defense of this attack, Vogt shot down two [[Avro Lancaster]] bombers from the RCAF [[405 Maritime Patrol Squadron|No. 405 Squadron]] or the RAF [[No. 582 Squadron RAF|No. 582 Squadron]] in aerial combat west of [[Cologne]].{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|pp=390\u2013391}}\n\nRadener led his 7. ''Staffel'' during [[Operation Bodenplatte]] on 1 January 1945, an attempt at gaining [[air superiority]] during the stagnant stage of the Battle of the Bulge.{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=408}} II. ''Gruppe'', under the leadership of ''Major'' [[Anton Hackl]] was based at [[Nordhorn]] at attacked the [[Haren Airport|Evere Airfield]] at [[Brussels]]. Together with III. ''Gruppe'', which was led by ''Hauptmann'' [[Walter Krupinski]], the attack on Evere was the only successful mission.{{sfn|Girbig|1997|p=199}} II. ''Gruppe'' lost 13 Fw&nbsp;190s destroyed and two damaged. Nine of its pilots were missing; five were killed and four captured. While III. ''Gruppe'' lost six Bf&nbsp;109s and four pilots, one of them was captured, the others were killed. Allied losses are given at Evere as 32 fighters, 22 twin-engine aircraft and 13 four-engine aircraft destroyed, plus another nine single-, six twin- and one four-engine aircraft damaged.{{sfn|Manrho|P\u00fctz|2004|p=195}}\n\nOn 29 January 1945, Hackl was appointed ''[[Geschwaderkommodore]]'' (wing commander) of [[Jagdgeschwader 300|''Jagdgeschwader'' 300]] (JG&nbsp;300\u2014300th Fighter Wing). In consequence, Radener was handed command of II. ''Gruppe'' of JG&nbsp;26 while command of 7. ''Staffel'' passed on to ''Leutnant'' Gottfried Dietze.{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=431}} On 22 February 1945, Radener was transferred to take command II. ''Gruppe'' of JG&nbsp;300 on request by Hackl. Radener was awarded the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross]] ({{lang|de|Ritterkreuz des Eisernen Kreuzes}}) on 12 March 1945 for his service in JG&nbsp;26.{{sfn|Caldwell|1991|p=337}}\n\n==Later life and death==\n[[File:Das Ehrenmal der Bundeswehr.jpg|thumb|(undeswehr Memorial, the [[Federal Ministry of Defence (Germany)|Federal Ministry of Defence]] in the back]]\nFollowing World War II, Radener joined the post-war ''[[Bundesluftwaffe]]''. ''Hauptmann'' Radener was killed in a flying accident flying a [[Canadian Car and Foundry]] manufactured varaint of the [[North American T-6 Texan]] \"AA+637\" on 8 January 1957 near [[Pei\u00dfenberg]].<ref>{{ASN accident|title=AA+637|id=121875|accessdate=6 April 2020|wikibase=yes}}</ref> He is listed on the [[:de:Ehrenmal der Bundeswehr|''Ehrenmal der Bundeswehr'']] (Bundeswehr Memorial).{{sfn|Ehrenmal der Bundeswehr}} Radener was practicing a [[Spin (aerodynamics)|spin]] during a refresher course. He was the first ''Bundesluftwaffe'' pilot to die in a flying accident.{{sfn|Meyer|2010|p=1}}\n\n==Summary of career==\n===Aerial victory claims===\nAccording to Obermaier, Radener was credited with 37 aerial victories all which claimed over the Western Front, including 17 heavy bombers.{{sfn|Obermaier|1989|p=183}} Matthews and Foreman, authors of ''Luftwaffe Aces \u2014 Biographies and Victory Claims'', researched the [[German Federal Archives]] and found records for 23 aerial victories, plus 15 further unconfirmed claims. All of his aerial victories were claimed over the [[Allies of World War II|Western Allies]] and includes twelve four-engined bombers.{{sfn|Matthews|Foreman|2015|pp=998\u2013999}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders collapsible collapsed\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none; text-align:right; width: 100%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"10\" | Chronicle of aerial victories\n|-\n| colspan=\"10\" style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n{{legend2|#e3d9ff|This and the \u2013 (dash) indicates unwitnessed aerial victory claims for which Radener did not receive credit. |border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}<br />\n{{legend2|#C0EFBA|This along with the * (asterisk) indicates an ''Herausschuss'' (separation shot)\u2014a severely damaged heavy bomber forced to separate from his combat box which was counted as an aerial victory.|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}<br />\n{{legend2|pink;|This along with the & (ampersand) indicates a ''endg\u00fcltige Vernichtung'' (final destruction)\u2014a ''[[coup de gr\u00e2ce]]'' inflicted on an already damaged heavy bomber.|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}<br />\n{{legend2|#faecc8|This and the ? (question mark) indicates information discrepancies listed by Caldwell, Prien, Stemmer, Rodeike, Bock, Matthews and Foreman.|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Claim\n!scope=\"col\"| Date\n!scope=\"col\"| Time\n!scope=\"col\" width=\"100px\"| Type\n!scope=\"col\"| Location\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"border-left: 3px solid grey;\" | Claim\n!scope=\"col\"| Date\n!scope=\"col\"| Time\n!scope=\"col\" width=\"100px\"| Type\n!scope=\"col\"| Location\n|-\n! colspan=\"10\" | \u2013 4. ''Staffel'' of ''Jagdgeschwader'' 26 \"Schlageter\" \u2013{{sfn|Matthews|Foreman|2015|p=998}}<br /><small>On the Western Front \u2014 28 February \u2013 July 1943</small>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#e3d9ff;\" | {{Center|\u2014}}\n| 13 March 1943\n| style=\"background:#faecc8\" | 15:10?{{Refn|According to Matthews and Foreman claimed at 15:33.{{sfn|Matthews|Foreman|2015|p=998}}|group=\"Note\"}}\n| [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]]\n| south of [[Belleville-sur-Mer|Belleville]]{{sfn|Prien|Stemmer|Rodeike|Bock|2010|p=554}}<br />east of [[\u00c9taples]]{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=36}}\n| style=\"border-left: 3px solid grey;\" | 2\n| 22 June 1943\n| 09:34\n| [[Republic P-47 Thunderbolt|P-47]]\n| {{Convert|10|-|15|km|mi|abbr=on}} northwest of [[Domburg]]{{sfn|Prien|Stemmer|Rodeike|Bock|2010|p=555}}{{sfn|Caldwell|1998|p=106}}\n|-\n| 1\n| 3 May 1943\n| 06:50\n| Spitfire\n| {{Convert|20|km|mi|abbr=on}} west of the [[Baie de Somme]]{{sfn|P