 Barradas]]\n* [[Jos\u00e9 de Bustamante y Guerra]]\n* [[\u00c1ngel Laborde]]\n|\n* [[Fernando Miyares y Gonz\u00e1les]]\n* [[Juan Domingo de Monteverde|Domingo de Monteverde]]\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Tom\u00e1s Boves]]\n* [[Juan Manuel Cajigal]]\n* [[Pablo Morillo]]\n* Juan de los Reyes Vargas\n* [[Francisco Montalvo y Ambulodi|Francisco Montalvo]]\n* [[Juan Jos\u00e9 de S\u00e1mano y Uribarri|Juan de S\u00e1mano]], Viceroy of New Granada\n* [[Miguel de la Torre|Miguel de la Torre y Pando]]\n* [[Francisco Tom\u00e1s Morales]]\n* [[Sebasti\u00e1n de la Calzada]]\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Barreiro Manj\u00f3n]]\n* [[Melchior Aymerich|Melchor Aymerich]], President of the Quito Audiencia\n* [[Jos\u00e9 de Canterac]]\n* [[Basilio Garc\u00eda]], Coronel\n* [[Agust\u00edn Agualongo]]\n|\n* [[Francisco Javier de El\u00edo]]\n* [[Gaspar de Vigodet]]\n* [[Bernardo de Velasco]]\n* [[Santiago de Liniers|Santiago de Liniers y Bremond]]\n* [[Vicente Nieto]], President of the [[Real Audiencia of Charcas|Charcas Audiencia]]\n|\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Fernando de Abascal y Sousa]]\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel de Goyeneche, 1st Count of Guaqui|Jos\u00e9 Manuel de Goyeneche]]\n* [[P\u00edo de Trist\u00e1n|P\u00edo Trist\u00e1n]]\n* [[Joaqu\u00edn de la Pezuela]]\n* [[Pedro Antonio Ola\u00f1eta]]\n* [[Jos\u00e9 de la Serna e Hinojosa]]\n* [[Jos\u00e9 de Canterac]]\n* [[Jer\u00f3nimo Vald\u00e9s]]\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00f3n Rodil y Campillo]]\n* [[Vicente Benavides]]\n* [[Antonio Pareja]]\n* [[Juan Francisco S\u00e1nchez]]\n* [[Gabino Ga\u00ednza]]\n* [[Mariano Osorio]]\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Ord\u00f3\u00f1ez]]\n* [[Rafael Maroto]]\n* [[Casimiro Marc\u00f3 del Pont]]\n* [[Antonio de Quintanilla]]\n|}\n</div>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Spain|Latin America|War|politics}}\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Age of Revolution]]\n* [[British Legions]]\n* [[List of foreign volunteers]]\n* [[Insurgent privateer]]\n* [[Philippine Revolution]]\n* [[Spanish reconquest of Mexico]]\n* [[Royalist (Spanish American Revolution)|Royalist]]\n* [[Latin American wars of independence]]\n* [[Wars of national liberation]]\n* [[History of South America]]\n* [[History of Mexico]]\n* [[New Spain]]\n* [[Spanish East Indies]]\n* [[Timeline of the Spanish American wars of independence]]\n* [[Timeline of Mexican War of Independence]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Cnote2 Begin|liststyle=upper-alpha}}\n{{Cnote2|Note A|[[Portuguese invasion of the Banda Oriental (1811\u201312)|First invasion]] of the [[Banda Oriental]] by the Portuguese army led by Diogo de Sousa in 1811 to annex the territory, which during the colonial period was disputed between Spain and Portugal. Not for destroy the independent government of Buenos Aires. In 1816 he invaded the Banda Oriental again and [[Portuguese conquest of the Banda Oriental|conquered]] it after a military campaign that lasted until 1820.}}\n{{Cnote2|Note B|During the course of the war, the various independent states that were formed at the beginning of the war went through different processes that changed them politically. This was due to reasons such as the overthrow of the government by the royalists and their subsequent restoration (for example, Chile and Venezuela), and also by the union of independent states that came to form a new political entity (Gran Colombia and the Mexican Empire).}}\n{{Cnote2|Note C|Due to the difficulty of representing in the infobox all the political stages of the independent states that suffered interruption in their process of separation from the Spanish Monarchy or that merged with other States to create a new political entity, or both, they will only appear in their final stage with which they managed to consolidate. Chile (1817\u20131826), Gran Colombia (1819\u20131824), M\u00e9xico (1821\u20131829), Peru (1821\u20131826), and Bolivia [[Self-determination]] from United Provinces of the R\u00edo de la Plata and Peru(1825).}}\n{{Cnote2|Note D|Mexico in its consolidation stage was organized as an [[First Mexican Empire|empire]] from 1821 to 1823. When the empire was dissolved, Mexico was reorganized as a [[First Mexican Republic|republic]] and the Central American territories that were part of the empire were reorganized into a new political entity called the United Provinces of Central America.}}\n{{Cnote2|Note E|Spain's Royal Army also was in the Mexican side, because the royalist criollo Colonel [[Agust\u00edn de Iturbide]] that joined the pro-independence side.}}\n{{Cnote2|Note F|During the course of the war, the United Provinces organized three land forces that fought on different fronts and periods: the army that confronted the royalists of Montevideo, the [[Army of the North]] and the [[Army of the Andes]]. In the maritime area, the government organized a naval force in 1811, which was [[Battle of San Nicol\u00e1s|destroyed in battle]] in that same year, so in 1813 he organized a second naval force that was operative until the [[Battle of Buceo|decisive victory]] obtained in 1814. He then used corsairs in the sea until the end of the war.}}\n{{Cnote2|Note G|In 1817, after the [[Battle of Chacabuco|triumph of the independents in Chacabuco]] and the subsequent restoration of the Chilean government, the [[Chilean Army]] was again organized, which fought along with the Army of the Andes in the center-south zone of Chile. Later, both armies would form the [[Liberating Expedition of Peru]], although a part of the Chilean force remained fighting in the country until its territorial consolidation. As for the maritime area, between 1817 and 1818 the [[Chilean Navy]] ([[First Chilean Navy Squadron]]) was founded and would operate until the end of the war. Between 1817 and 1820, Chile also used corsairs in the sea.}}\n{{Cnote2|Note H|In its consolidation phase, the Mexican government had as a land force the so-called [[Army of the Three Guarantees]], while to fight in the sea it founded the [[Mexican Navy]].}}\n{{Cnote2|Note I|Sailors and combatants recruited in [[United Kingdom]]. Sales of warships, weapons and ammunition.<ref>{{cite article |last=Blaufarb |first=Rafe  |year=2016 |title=Arms for Revolutions: Military Demobilization after the Napoleonic Wars and Latin American Independence|issn= |}}</ref><ref>{{cite article |last=Waddell |first=D. A. G. |year=1987 |title=British Neutrality and Spanish\u2014American Independence: The Problem of Foreign Enlistment |journal= |issn= |}}</ref>}}\n{{Cnote2|Note J|guerrillas or violent rebellions in many countries}}\n{{Cnote2|Note K|under flags of many belligerents}}\n{{Cnote2|Note L|The First Texas Independence, 1813. The green flag is the first flag of Texas independence. <ref> The First Texas Independence, 1813. Lopez 2013. Xlibris [https://books.google.es/books?hl=es&lr=&id=CY1YxzdwrSgC&oi=fnd&pg=PR3&dq=Texas+first+independence+1813&ots=6DeFllgrZK&sig=hxBlNAolwaBQOxz1zO62gjIOs4U#v=onepage&q&f=false]</ref>}}\n{{Cnote2|Note M|[[Republic of West Florida]] anexattion (1810). Rebellion of [[Republic of East Florida]] (1812).}} \n{{Cnote2|Note N|[[Insurgent privateers]] using many flags.}}\n{{Cnote2|Note O|diplomatic declaration exclusively.}} \n{{Cnote2 End}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n===Spanish America and Spain===\n{{Div col}}\n* Adelman, Jeremy. ''Sovereignty and Revolution in the Iberian Atlantic''. Princeton University Press 2006. {{ISBN|978-0691142777}}\n* Andrews, George Reid. \"Spanish American independence: A structural analysis.\" ''Latin American Perspectives'' (1985): 105-132. [http://pics3441.upmf-grenoble.fr/articles/inde/Spanish%20American%20Independence%20A%20Structural%20Analysis.pdf online]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* Andrien, Kenneth J. and Lyman L. Johnson. ''The Political Economy of Spanish America in the Age of Revolution, 1750\u20131850''. Albuquerque, University of New Mexico Press, 1994. {{ISBN|978-0-8263-1489-5}}\n* Anna, Timothy.. ''Spain & the Loss of Empire''. Lincoln, University of Nebraska Press, 1983. {{ISBN|978-0-8032-1014-1}}\